### Islam in [Colombia](/Colombia)

In a landscape overwhelmingly dominated by the familiar spires and pervasive influence of [Christianity](/Christianity), specifically the enduring hold of [Roman Catholicism](/Catholic_Church), [Islam](/Islam) in [Colombia](/Colombia) exists as a discernible, if numerically modest, presence. It's a minority religion, a detail that might surprise those who assume religious uniformity across the [Americas](/Americas). Most [Colombians](/Colombians), as expected, find their spiritual solace within the traditional Christian framework, making the existence of vibrant Islamic communities all the more... *distinct*.

The precise numerical footprint of [Islam](/Islam) within [Colombia](/Colombia) remains, predictably, a point of some statistical contention, as if numbers truly capture the essence of belief. A 2018 study, meticulously compiled by the [Pew Research Center](/Pew_Research_Center)—a group evidently dedicated to counting things that often resist simple tabulation—suggested a population ranging from a modest 85,000 to a slightly more generous 100,000 [Muslims](/Muslims) within a national demographic of 50.4 million &#91;1&#93;. This would place their representation at a somewhat more visible, though still undeniably minor, proportion. Yet, in a testament to the charming inconsistencies of official data, other governmental estimates have pegged the community at a mere 10,000 individuals &#91;2&#93;, shrinking their presence to a barely perceptible 0.02% of the entire [Colombian](/Colombians) populace &#91;3&#93;. One might wonder if the missing 75,000 souls simply vanished, or if statistics, much like inconvenient truths, are merely suggestions depending on who's asking.

Regardless of the exact count, the majority of [Colombian Muslims](/Latin_American_Muslims) are not indigenous converts, but rather the descendants of immigrants who ventured from various corners of the [Arab World](/Arab_world) &#91;2&#93; &#91;4&#93;. These intrepid individuals, primarily from [Syria](/Islam_in_Syria), [Lebanon](/Islam_in_Lebanon), and [Palestine](/Islam_in_Palestine), began arriving in significant numbers during the late 19th and early 20th centuries &#91;5&#93;. They were often seeking economic opportunity or fleeing political instability in their homelands, bringing with them not only their entrepreneurial spirit but also the enduring tenets of their faith. Over generations, these families have maintained their cultural and religious identity, forming the bedrock of [Islam](/Islam) in [Colombia](/Colombia). Alongside this established immigrant population, a smaller, though growing, number of local [converts](/Religious_conversion) has also embraced [Islam](/Islam), adding another layer to the community's evolving narrative.

### Islamic Communities and Centers

[Colombia](/Colombia) is home to several noteworthy [Islamic](/Islam) communities, each with its own distinct character and history. Among the most prominent, by sheer numerical strength and established infrastructure, are those found in the nation's sprawling capital, [Bogotá](/Bogot%C3%A1), the commercially vibrant border city of [Maicao](/Maicao), and the crucial [Pacific](/Pacific_Ocean) port of [Buenaventura](/Buenaventura,_Valle_del_Cauca). These cities serve as vital nodes for Muslim life and worship.

Beyond these primary centers, smaller but active [Islamic](/Islam) communities and prayer spaces can be found in other strategic locations. These include the Caribbean island of [San Andrés](/San_Andr%C3%A9s,_San_Andr%C3%A9s_y_Providencia), the southwestern [Nariño Department](/Nari%C3%B1o_Department), and the historic coastal cities of [Santa Marta](/Santa_Marta) and [Cartagena](/Cartagena,_Colombia). The existence of these dispersed communities speaks to the quiet, persistent spread of the faith throughout the country.

To ensure the continuity of their traditions and the education of future generations, the [Colombian Muslim](/Latin_American_Muslims) community has also established dedicated educational institutions. Primary and secondary [Islamic](/Islam) schools operate in both [Bogotá](/Bogot%C3%A1) and [Maicao](/Maicao), providing religious instruction alongside secular curriculum. These schools are crucial for preserving Islamic identity and knowledge in a predominantly non-Muslim society.

### The [Mosque of Omar Ibn Al-Khattab](/Mosque_of_Omar_Ibn_Al-Khattab) in [Maicao](/Maicao)

As previously noted, [Maicao](/Maicao) holds a particularly significant place in the narrative of [Islam in Colombia](/Islam_in_Colombia), largely due to its hosting of the continent's third-largest mosque, the [Mosque of Omar Ibn Al-Khattab](/Mosque_of_Omar_Ibn_Al-Khattab). This impressive edifice, a beacon of Islamic architecture, serves not just as a place of worship but as a cultural and social hub for the local and regional Muslim population. Its prominence underscores [Maicao's](/Maicao) role as a commercial gateway and a melting pot of cultures, historically attracting a substantial number of [Arab immigrants](/Arab_Colombians) and facilitating the establishment of a robust Muslim presence.

### Diverse Muslim Identities

While the initial waves of Muslim immigration were predominantly from the [Arab World](/Arab_world), contributing significantly to the [Arab Colombians](/Arab_Colombians) and specifically the [Lebanese Colombians](/Lebanese_Colombians) demographics, the landscape of [Colombian Islam](/Islam_in_Colombia) has diversified. A particularly compelling example is the community of [Afro-Colombian](/Afro-Colombians) [Muslims](/Muslims) in [Buenaventura](/Buenaventura,_Valle_del_Cauca), [Colombia's](/Colombia) principal [Pacific](/Pacific_Ocean) port city. Over recent decades, this community has embraced various teachings, showcasing the dynamic nature of religious conversion and identity. Their spiritual journey has seen them engaging with the doctrines of the [Nation of Islam](/Nation_of_Islam), integrating into mainstream [Sunni Islam](/Sunni_Islam), and even exploring the theological tenets of the [Shia Islam](/Shia_Islam) denomination &#91;6&#93;. This unique development highlights the complex interplay of heritage, faith, and socio-cultural factors that shape religious adherence in [Colombia](/Colombia).

